  "answer": "The critic misreads the target. The target’s mechanism is that Egypt’s ideological-theological structure allowed ritual delegation of military authority without fracturing *divine kingship* — meaning the core theological institution of a single, ritually continuous pharaonic office persisted. The forbidden case documents political fragmentation (rival dynasties), not theological fracturing of the office itself. Libyan and Nubian challengers adopted and claimed the same divine kingship title and ritual role; they did not replace it with an alternative legitimation principle. The mechanism therefore accommodates the observation: Egypt’s divine kingship survived as an institution even when multiple claimants competed for it, whereas Hittite and Mycenaean charismatic authority dissolved when the king personally failed, because their legitimation structure lacked the same capacity for ritual delegation. No contradiction exists between political fragmentation and institutional-theological continuity."
